person.note: Godwin's younger brother Joseph. Godwin records his death in 1825. It seems likely that he dies in prison. Joseph Godwin seems to have been apprenticed to Thomas Raven of Fakenham, grocer and draper, in 1771 (National Archive IR1/58 f24). Raven may have been the father in law of Philip Hull Godwin. Jospeh married Mary Jex on 1 Devember 1776, and had six children, John Jex (1780), Maryy Anne (1781), Charles (1783), Harriet 1785), Phebe 1788, and William 1792. Joseph seems to have moved to London and become the agent of Francis and Thomas Lea of Kiderminster, at their London warehouse in 10, Bagnio Court, Newgate Street. (JG refers to lea in his letter from Bagnio Court in July 1801). Joseph died in the Fleet Prison in 1825 after imprisonment for debt in 1821. Godwin notes his death. He also notes the death of Mrs Jo Godwin: 'Mrs Jo Godwin dies', 1834-03-05.
